        <p>I am a moderate Republican who opposes hate-crimes legislation. I do not consider this view ''anti-gay'' (editorial, Oct. 22).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>I am a moderate Republican who opposes hate-crimes legislation. I do not consider this view ''anti-gay'' (editorial, Oct. 22).</p>
        <p>A murder is a murder: there is no precedent in our legal system to increase the harshness of a sentence based on the motive for the crime. If someone kills a gay friend of mine, I want that person to receive an equally harsh sentence whether the motive is jealousy or hate.</p>
        <p>How do we determine which groups should qualify for these laws? If a murder takes place over political views, is that a hate crime? If someone is murdered because of his or her profession, like an abortion doctor, is that a hate crime? We have a difficult enough time determining whether someone has committed a crime; determining motive is even harder.</p>
        <p>For all of these reasons, it is unfair to assume that Congressional Republicans opposed to hate-crimes legislation are bowing to ''anti-gay'' voices.</p>
        <p>JOHN BASH  Cambridge, Mass., Oct. 22, 2000</p>
      </block>
